1 0 0 1 50 742 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 728 Tm (This paper makes five contributions.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 714 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 700 Tm (1. It identifies a **governed-unit problem** in contemporary AI governance discourse.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 686 Tm (2. It distinguishes governance more sharply from evaluation, attribution, and control.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 672 Tm (3. It defines the **action system** as a more realistic governed unit for deployed agent) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 658 Tm (systems.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 644 Tm (4. It analyzes where governance power actually resides: not only leverage, but authority,) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 630 Tm (review rights, contestability, and trace ownership.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 616 Tm (5. It proposes a governance-aware reporting schema for serious claims about agent systems.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 602 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 588 Tm (## 2. Governance Is Not Evaluation, Attribution, or Control) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 574 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 560 Tm (This paper belongs to a sequence of distinctions, but it must also stand on its own.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 546 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 532 Tm (- **Evaluation** asks what should be measured, and at what unit.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 518 Tm (- **Attribution** asks where an observed property properly belongs.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 504 Tm (- **Control** asks where system trajectory can be altered through feasible intervention.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 490 Tm (- **Governance** asks how legitimate authority, oversight, intervention rights,) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 476 Tm (auditability, and accountability are arranged around the system.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 462 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 448 Tm (Governance therefore overlaps with control but is not reducible to it. A party may possess) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 434 Tm (leverage without possessing legitimate authority. A vendor may technically shape behavior) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 420 Tm (while a deployer bears formal responsibility. A human approver may be able to intervene but) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 406 Tm (only through a narrow interface with poor visibility. A user may be affected by the system) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 392 Tm (without any meaningful contestation rights at all.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 378 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 364 Tm (The distinctive governance question is therefore not only **where can the system be) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 350 Tm (steered?** It is also **who is entitled to steer it, through what procedures, with what) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 336 Tm (visibility, under whose review, and with what residual accountability if things go wrong?**) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 322 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 308 Tm (## 3. Why Model-Centered Governance Became Insufficient) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 294 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 280 Tm (Model-centered governance made more sense when the dominant picture of AI behavior was) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 266 Tm (short-horizon text generation. In that setting, governing the model seemed close to) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 252 Tm (governing the system.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 238 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 224 Tm (That equivalence is eroding.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 210 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 196 Tm (Agent systems increasingly rely on:) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 182 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 168 Tm (- orchestration layers that sequence behavior over many steps,) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 154 Tm (- tools that create external side effects,) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 140 Tm (- memory that persists context and identity,) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 126 Tm (- approval layers that condition action rights,) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 112 Tm (- execution environments that define what can actually be touched,) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 98 Tm (- logging systems that determine reconstructability,) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 84 Tm (- and humans who retain veto, escalation, or correction rights.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 70 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 56 Tm (These are not decorative wrappers. They partly determine the real system that acts in the) Tj
ET
endstream
