1 0 0 1 50 742 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 728 Tm (If governance is attached to the action system, then its real loci become easier to map.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 714 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 700 Tm (### 5.1 Permissions and delegated rights) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 686 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 672 Tm (Which actions are allowed? Which require approval? Which are barred? Permission design is) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 658 Tm (often a more immediate governance instrument than any change to model weights.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 644 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 630 Tm (### 5.2 Orchestration and review pathways) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 616 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 602 Tm (Workflow logic can force approvals, insert reviews, require decomposition, expose) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 588 Tm (intermediate state, or silently execute chained actions. Governance power often resides in) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 574 Tm (how these pathways are designed.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 560 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 546 Tm (### 5.3 Persistence and continuity policy) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 532 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 518 Tm (If memory can be edited, deleted, or rendered visible to auditors, continuity becomes) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 504 Tm (governable. If it is opaque, sticky, or hard to contest, governance weakens.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 490 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 476 Tm (### 5.4 Infrastructure and account control) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 462 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 448 Tm (Credential ownership, network boundaries, deployment accounts, runtime privileges, and) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 434 Tm (service bindings determine who actually possesses operational authority.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 420 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 406 Tm (### 5.5 Oversight and interruption rights) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 392 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 378 Tm (Who may pause the system, override it, correct it, or shut it down? Through what interface?) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 364 Tm (With what visibility? These are governance questions, not merely operational conveniences.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 350 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 336 Tm (### 5.6 Logging, trace retention, and contestability) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 322 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 308 Tm (A system that leaves weak traces is hard to audit and hard to contest. Trace architecture) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 294 Tm (shapes whether governance can later be reviewed, disputed, or reconstructed.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 280 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 266 Tm (## 6. What Current Governance Frameworks Often Miss) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 252 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 238 Tm (The weakness of many current frameworks is not that they are pointless. It is that they) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 224 Tm (under-specify the governed unit.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 210 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 50 196 Tm (- **Model cards** often omit permission structure, orchestration policy, memory editing) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 182 Tm (rights, and oversight roles.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 168 Tm (- **Frontier-model debates** may over-focus on weights while under-describing deployer) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 154 Tm (authority and runtime boundaries.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 140 Tm (- **Procurement reviews** may ask what model is used without asking who controls) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 126 Tm (credentials, logging, rollback, and approvals.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 112 Tm (- **Public safety claims** may attribute trustworthiness to the model when much of the) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 98 Tm (actual governance work is being done by wrappers, humans, and infrastructure.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 84 Tm (- **Responsibility assignment** may drift toward the model provider while operational power) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 70 Tm (is concentrated in deployers, platform owners, or integrators.) Tj
1 0 0 1 50 56 Tm () Tj
